so that it is more protective against fear, and more defensive through manliness, and that it destroys the outside, and preserves the inside; they hold the quietness of the hands, but the movements are healthy; and as for children, they do not beget them in common, but the benefits are the same; for it belongs to the one who nurtures it, and the one who educates it. This is not unfair. And this is what the common law says, as the Pythagoreans say, as if the women who were beggars and after the hearth had become like fishes, they would try to be unjust; but the injustice of a man is the intercourse that takes place. but as for speaking, they are accustomed to be seen; they are accustomed to be silent when they are absent, but they are so accustomed that they are able to have both present and non-present. so it doesn't have that of Hesiod either.
